### Search before asking

- [x] I searched in the [issues](https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/issues) and found nothing similar.

### Describe the bug

Now that https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/issues/1484 has changed the default of `MapperFeature.DEFAULT_VIEW_INCLUSION` to `false` in 3.0, I think `DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNEXPECTED_VIEW_PROPERTIES` should be either disabled by default, or only throw exception when `MapperFeature.DEFAULT_VIEW_INCLUSION` is set to `true`, otherwise the behavior is very annoying and confusing for IMO no good reason.

### Version Information

3.0.0-rc3

### Reproduction

```java
	interface SafeToDeserialize {}

	private static class User {

		@JsonView(SafeToDeserialize.class)
		private String username;

		private String password;

		public User() {
		}

		public User(String username, String password) {
			this.username = username;
			this.password = password;
		}

		public String getUsername() {
			return username;
		}

		public void setUsername(String username) {
			this.username = username;
		}

		public String getPassword() {
			return password;
		}

		public void setPassword(String password) {
			this.password = password;
		}
	}

	@Test
	void test() {
		JsonMapper mapper = JsonMapper.builder()
				// Will be the default as of Jackson 3.O0.0-rc4
				.disable(MapperFeature.DEFAULT_VIEW_INCLUSION)
				.build();
		String data = "{\"username\":\"foo\",\"password\":\"bar\"}";
		User user = mapper.readerFor(User.class).withView(SafeToDeserialize.class).readValue(data);
		assertThat(user.getUsername()).isEqualTo("foo");
		assertThat(user.getPassword()).isNull();
	}
``` 


### Expected behavior

Currently this test require `disable(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNEXPECTED_VIEW_PROPERTIES)` to pass, which is confusing since password is not deserialized due to `MapperFeature.DEFAULT_VIEW_INCLUSION` now being disabled. The current behavior will be even more confusing with upcoming `MapperFeature.DEFAULT_VIEW_INCLUSION` set to `false` by default in Jackson 3.0.0-rc4.

### Additional context

This use case is very popular in Spring applications.
